03972nam a22005895i 9780822382041DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19961996ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223820417 a10.1515/97808223820412doi  a(DE-B1597)553536  a(OCoLC)1097085260  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN56.T7bK37 2000 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 aKaplan, Caren, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQuestions of Travel :bPostmodern Discourses of Displacement /cCaren Kaplan; Stanley Fish, Fredric Jameson. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1996] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tQUESTIONS OF TRAVEL -- t1 "THIS QUESTION OF MOVING" -- t2 BECOMING NOMAD -- t3 TRAVELING THEORISTS -- t4 POSTMODERN GEOGRAPHIES -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aContemporary theory is replete with metaphors of travel-displacement, diaspora, borders, exile, migration, nomadism, homelessness, and tourism to name a few. In Questions of Travel, Caren Kaplan explores the various metaphoric uses of travel and displacement in literary and feminist theory, traces the political implications of this "traveling theory," and shows how various discourses of displacement link, rather than separate, modernism and postmodernism.Addressing a wide range of writers, including Paul Fussell, Edward Said, James Clifford, Gilles Deleuze, Jean Baudrillard, Gayatri Spivak, Edward Soja, Doreen Massey, Chandra Mohanty, and Adrienne Rich, Kaplan demonstrates that symbols and metaphors of travel are used in ways that obscure key differences of power between nationalities, classes, races, and genders. Neither rejecting nor dismissing the powerful testimony of individual experiences of modern exile or displacement, Kaplan asks how mystified metaphors of travel might be avoided. With a focus on theory's colonial discourses, she reveals how these metaphors continue to operate in the seemingly liberatory critical zones of poststructuralism and feminist theory. The book concludes with a critique of the politics of location as a form of essentialist identity politics and calls for new feminist geographies of place and displacement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aLiterature, ModernxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature). 0aPostmodernism (Literature). 0aTravel in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aFish, Stanley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822382041zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822382041423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822382041.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles